          "body": "Verses 13-19 address the hardest test of the tongue: when it is under pressure in dispute, legal contest, and broken relationship. Verse 13 is one of the most practically applicable proverbs in the chapter: answering before hearing is folly and shame. The sequence is non-negotiable — hearing precedes answering; understanding precedes speaking. This is the epistemological humility that the fool of verse 2 entirely lacks. Verse 14 descends into the interior: the human spirit (*ruach*) can sustain bodily illness, but a broken spirit — no one can bear that. This proverb recognizes that inner collapse is more devastating than outer suffering, and it stands as an implicit pastoral argument for attending to the inner life of those under pressure. Verse 17 returns to the legal arena with a warning so important for justice that it should be posted in every courtroom: the first to plead his case always seems right — until cross-examination. One-sided testimony is structurally misleading, not because the speaker is necessarily lying but because truth in dispute requires adversarial testing. Verse 18 commends the lot as a way to end intractable disputes between powerful opponents — in Israel, the lot (*goral*) was a recognized mechanism for discerning God's will when human wisdom reached its limit (cf. Proverbs 16:33; Acts 1:26). Verse 19 closes this section with the chapter's most sobering relational warning: an offended brother is harder to recover than a fortified city, and contentions between former intimates become like iron bars on a citadel gate. Broken trust between the close is uniquely resistant to repair."
