        "number": 2,
        "title": "The real tower and the imagined wall — where the righteous and the rich run",
        "range": "18:9-12",
        "excerpt": "The name of the LORD is a strong tower; the righteous runs into it and is safe. (18:10)",
        "body": "Verse 10 is the theological center of Proverbs 18 and one of the most compressed theologies of refuge in the entire Old Testament. 'The name of the LORD is a strong tower' — in ancient Israelite culture, the name (*shem*) of a person or deity was not a label but a summary of character and presence. To invoke the name of the LORD was to appeal to everything He had revealed Himself to be: the God who passed before Moses declaring 'gracious, compassionate, slow to anger, abounding in lovingkindness and truth' (Exodus 34:6). The tower (*migdal oz* — tower of strength) is the image of military refuge, the last stronghold into which a city's population retreats when the outer walls have fallen. The righteous person 'runs' (*ruts*) into it — urgently, physically, directionally. Safety (*sagav* — to be set on high, beyond reach) is the outcome. This is not passive shelter; the righteous person actively flees to a specific, known refuge.\n\nVerse 11 is deliberately placed next to v. 10 without a connecting particle — the reader must supply 'but' or 'whereas.' A rich man's wealth is his strong city (*oz qiryah*) and a high wall — but only 'in his own imagination' (*maskit*). The word *maskit* denotes a mental image, a picture in the mind. The rich man's fortress is structurally identical in language to the LORD's tower (both are 'strong,' both offer a city-image of security) but differs in one catastrophic way: one is real, the other is a projection of the self-referential heart that the chapter has been diagnosing since verse 1. The self-isolator of v. 1 quarrels against sound wisdom; the rich man of v. 11 quarrels against reality itself, substituting his mental image for the actual state of his security.\n\nVerse 12 names the interior disposition that determines which tower a person runs to: haughty heart → destruction; humility → honor. This proverb echoes Proverbs 16:18 ('pride goes before destruction') and anticipates James 4:6 ('God opposes the proud but gives grace to the humble,' citing Proverbs 3:34). The sequence is not random — pride and humility are not simultaneous with their outcomes; they precede them. The person who has allowed pride to remain unchallenged has already chosen the imagined wall. Humility — the recognition that you are not the measure of your own security — is what positions a person to run toward the real tower.\n\nCharles Spurgeon preached on v. 10 that the name of the LORD is not a talisman or a formula but a Person: 'We do not trust in a name as a sound; we trust in a name as a revelation of him who bears it.' The tower is real because the One whose name it is, is real. Tim Keller's observation on Proverbs' security metaphors is relevant here: every false refuge is real enough to feel like a tower until the siege actually comes; it is only under actual pressure that the imagined wall reveals itself as imagination.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shem Yehovah* (name of the LORD) — the covenant name revealed at Exodus 3:14-15 and 34:5-7; not merely a title but the self-disclosure of character. *Sagav* (safe, v.10) — to be set on high, inaccessible to the enemy; the same verb appears in Psalm 20:1 ('the LORD answer you in the day of trouble; the name of the God of Jacob set you securely on high'). *Maskit* (imagination, v.11) — from *sakah*, to look; a mental image, a vision in the mind."
