        "body": "Verses 13-19 address the most socially demanding test of the tongue: adversarial contexts where the pressure to speak quickly, judge partially, or defend one's position is highest. Verse 13 is the epistemological anchor: the sequence listening → understanding → answering is non-negotiable. To answer before hearing is not merely impolite — it is *ivvelet* (folly, the noun form of the same root as the fool of chapter 1) and *kelimmah* (shame, the public exposure of having been shown wrong). The proverb does not merely counsel patience; it diagnoses premature speech as the intellectual equivalent of the fool's self-display — both substitute the self's prior conclusion for the reality that hearing would supply.\n\nVerse 14 is the chapter's most introspective observation: the human *ruach* (spirit, the animating inner person) can sustain bodily illness, but a broken spirit — who can bear it? This proverb appears without direct connection to the surrounding legal material, but its placement is not accidental. People who have been wrongly judged, whose case was decided before they were heard (v. 13), whose testimony was dismissed by the powerful (v. 23), suffer the precise injury v. 14 names: a crushed inner person. The proverb is simultaneously a pastoral warning and an implicit rebuke of the hasty judge: the spirit you wound with your premature verdict may be one that cannot recover.\n\nVerse 17 is one of Proverbs' most forensically sophisticated observations: 'The first to plead his case seems right, until another comes and examines him.' The verb *chaqar* — to cross-examine, to search out — is the same word used of God's exhaustive knowledge (Psalm 139:1) and of Wisdom's searching of hearts (Proverbs 20:27). Justice requires the adversarial process; one-sided testimony is structurally misleading even when the speaker is sincere. This proverb is the ancient equivalent of *audi alteram partem* — hear the other side. Verse 18 extends the logic: when even cross-examination fails to resolve a dispute between powerful opponents, the lot (*goral*) is a legitimate recourse. In Israelite practice, the lot was not random chance but a recognized mechanism for discerning the LORD's will (cf. Proverbs 16:33, 'the lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the LORD'; also Acts 1:26). The chapter acknowledges that some human conflicts exceed human resolution.\n\nVerse 19 closes this section with the chapter's most sobering relational verdict. An offended brother (*ach pasah* — a brother who has been transgressed against) is harder to win back than a fortified city, and contentions between former intimates become like the bars of a citadel gate. The comparison is deliberately hyperbolic and deliberately military: the most intimate human relationship, once fractured by offense, becomes the most impenetrable defensive structure. Peter Davids' observation on the parallel James 4:1-2 material is relevant here: desires that lead to conflict between believers produce a kind of relational militarization — each party fortifies against the other precisely because the closeness that made the relationship valuable makes the wound harder to expose and heal.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ivvelet* (folly, v.13) — the same root as *evil* (fool) in 1:7, 17:28; not stupidity but willful resistance to correction. *Ruach naka* (broken spirit, v.14) — *naka* means stricken, smitten, as by a wound; the spirit that has been hit and cannot recover. *Chaqar* (examines, v.17) — to penetrate, to search out thoroughly; the same verb in Job 13:9 where Job challenges God to examine him. *Parad* (separated, v.18) — the same root as v.1; the lot *separates* opponents in the positive sense that the self-isolator of v.1 separates himself in the negative sense."
