        "excerpt": "Death and life are in the power of the tongue, and those who love it will eat its fruit. (18:21)",
        "body": "Verses 20-21 bring the chapter's extended meditation on speech to its absolute conclusion. Verse 20's alimentary metaphor — the fruit of the mouth, the produce of the lips, filling a man's belly and satisfying him — frames speech as sustenance: what comes out of you feeds you, for life or for ruin. Verse 21 then issues the chapter's most absolute verdict in eleven Hebrew words: death and life are in the hand (*yad*) of the tongue, and those who love it will eat its fruit. The word *yad* — hand — is the organ of agency, control, and power. The tongue is not a passive conduit; it is an active agent with the grip of a hand on two ultimate outcomes: life and death.\n\nThis is not hyperbole. The entire chapter has been demonstrating it. The fool's mouth is his ruin (v. 7). The whisperer's words penetrate to the innermost self and corrupt unseen (v. 8). The hasty answer produces folly and shame (v. 13). The first to plead seems right until tested — speech that is not cross-examined distorts justice (v. 17). Those who 'love' the tongue — who indulge its exercise without discipline, who savor the use of words for their own sake — will eat whatever harvest their speech has produced. The harvest is the speaker's own, for better or for worse. James 3:1-12 is the New Testament expansion of v. 21: the tongue is a fire, a world of iniquity, set on fire by hell; no human being can tame it. James does not contradict Proverbs' realism — he extends it into the post-Pentecost era where the Spirit provides what no self-discipline can achieve.\n\nVerse 22 pauses the moral anatomy with a note of straightforward gratitude: finding a wife is finding a good thing and obtaining *ratson* (favor, divine pleasure) from the LORD. The word *ratson* is the same used of sacrifices acceptable to God and of His delight in the upright (Proverbs 11:1; 15:8). Marriage is placed in the category of divine gift received, not human achievement secured. Reformed commentators from Calvin (*Commentary on Proverbs*, 1564) to Kidner note that the proverb is not a statement about all possible marriages but about marriage itself as an institution — the good thing that a genuinely good wife represents is a grace that has God as its ultimate source (cf. Proverbs 19:14: 'a prudent wife is from the LORD').\n\nVerse 24 closes the chapter with its most theologically resonant image. A man of many companions (*rea* — neighbors, associates) 'may come to ruin' — shallow networks of acquaintance are structurally fragile; they multiply points of potential betrayal without the depth to sustain genuine need. But *there is* a friend (*ahav*, one who loves) who clings (*daveq*) closer than a brother. The verb *daveq* is covenantal: Ruth to Naomi ('she clung to her,' Ruth 1:14), Israel to the LORD ('hold fast to Him,' Deuteronomy 10:20), husband to wife in Genesis 2:24. This friend is not merely affectionate but loyal with a covenantal tenacity that exceeds even biological kinship. The chapter that opened with the self-isolating fool who quarrels against all sound wisdom closes with the image of the one friend whose cling cannot be broken. The theological trajectory from the false refuge of v. 11 (the imagined wall) to the real refuge of v. 10 (the LORD's name) finds its relational expression here: the friend who sticks closer than a brother images — and in Christ becomes — the covenant loyalty of God Himself toward those who run into His name.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yad lashon* (power of the tongue, v.21) — literally 'hand of the tongue'; *yad* is consistently the word for power, agency, and dominion (cf. Psalm 106:10; Isaiah 49:24). *Ratson* (favor, v.22) — divine pleasure, delight, approval; used of God's reception of acceptable sacrifice and His delight in the upright. *Daveq* (sticks, v.24) — to cling, to cleave, the covenantal adhesion of Ruth 1:14 and Genesis 2:24; not mere sentiment but structural loyalty that holds under pressure."
